    <text id="A8046T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Baldwin states that he has "no position" to which he can appoint McCue in the
                    military.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    Inspector General's Office
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1861-05-27">May 27 1861</date>
                        <name type="place">Head Quarters, Richmond,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>My Dear Sir.</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>I regret that I have in my gift or under my control no position in which I could
                    employ your capacities as a military man. I am satisfied you have the natural
                    gifts of a soldier &amp; that you will in any field win for yourself
                    reputation &amp; promotion if you get a fair chance.</p>
                <p>As far as my opinion can avail as the result of a life long acquaintance I am
                    bound to testify in your behalf.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Very truly<lb/>Your friend</salute>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="underline">John B. Baldwin</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <seg type="postscript">
                        <name type="recipient">John H. McCue <abbr expan="Esquire"
                        >Esq.</abbr></name>
                    </seg>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
